  "opinion": "As a woman who's spent decades working as an electrician in Naples, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can quietly undermine people's confidence in fields like STEM. Stereotype threat isn't some abstract academic concept—it's when someone feels their identity might be judged negatively in a situation where they're expected to perform well. For example, when I'm fixing a circuit at a construction site and a young male colleague jokes about how 'girls don't understand electronics,' it triggers that anxious feeling I've carried since I was a kid. I remember my father, who had no formal education, telling me that 'women are too emotional for math,' and that belief stuck with me long after I learned to wire a transformer. The problem isn't just about individual cases—it's systemic. When schools and workplaces don't address these biases openly, they reinforce the idea that certain groups don't belong in STEM. But addressing it doesn't mean we have to do it with lectures or big speeches. In my work, I've found that simple things like having women and non-binary people in leadership roles at the job site, or creating 'no judgment' zones where people can ask questions without fear of being mocked, make a real difference. It's not about changing people's minds overnight—it's about building spaces where everyone feels safe to try. I worry that because I'm anxious, I might not be able to speak up as much as I should, but I've learned that small, consistent actions matter more than grand gestures. The key is to make sure that when someone says, 'I don't know,' it's not because they feel they're failing, but because they're still learning.",
